**Severity:** High

**OWASP Top 10 2021 Category:** A1: Broken Access Control

**Detailed Solution:**

1. Open Internet Information Services (IIS) Manager.
2. Select the website or application for which you want to configure cache control.
3. Right-click on the website or application and select "Properties".
4. In the "Properties" window, select the "HTTP Response Headers" tab.
5. Click the "Add..." button.
6. In the "Name" field, enter "Cache-Control".
7. In the "Value" field, enter the desired cache-control directive. For example, to prevent the browser from caching the response, enter "no-cache".
8. Click the "OK" button to save your changes.

**Additional Notes:**

* The Cache-Control header is used to control how browsers and proxies cache responses from your web server.
* Improper configuration of the Cache-Control header can lead to security vulnerabilities such as cache poisoning and information disclosure.
* It is important to carefully consider the appropriate cache-control directives for your specific application.
